10 mcqs on the topic CONSTRUCTORS IN JAVA (Parameterless & Parameterized)

1)What is the main purpose of a constructor in Java?

A. To destroy an object
B. To initialize an object
C. To declare a method
D. To allocate memory manually

‚úÖ Correct Answer: B
2)Which of the following is a parameterless (default) constructor?

A. Student(int id) {}
B. Student() {}
C. void Student() {}
D. Student(void) {}

‚úÖ Correct Answer: B
3)What happens if no constructor is explicitly defined in a Java class?

A. Compilation error occurs
B. JVM creates a parameterized constructor
C. Java provides a default parameterless constructor
D. Object cannot be created

‚úÖ Correct Answer: C
4)class Test {
    int x;
    Test(int a) {
        x = a;
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Test t = new Test();
    }
}
What will be the output?

A. Program runs successfully
B. x will be initialized to 0
C. Compilation error
D. Runtime error

‚úÖ Correct Answer: C
5)Which of the following statements about constructors in Java is TRUE?

A. Constructors can be inherited
B. Constructors can be overridden
C. Constructors can be overloaded
D. Constructors must have a return type

‚úÖ Correct Answer: C
üìù Reason: Constructors can be overloaded but cannot be inherited or overridden and have no return type.
6)Why does the following code fail to compile?
‚ùå WRONG CODE
class Test {
    void Test() {
        System.out.println("Constructor called");
    }
}
‚úîÔ∏è CORRECT CODE
class Test {
    Test() {
        System.out.println("Constructor called");
    }
}

Concept: Constructor must not have a return type.

7 )‚Äî Parameterized Constructor Written as Method
‚ùì Question
Is Test(int x) a constructor? Justify.
‚ùå WRONG CODE
class Test {
    int Test(int x) {
        return x;
    }
}
‚úîÔ∏è CORRECT CODE
class Test {
    Test(int x) {
        System.out.println(x);
    }
}
Concept: Constructors cannot return values.

8) ‚Äî Missing Default Constructor
‚ùì Question
What happens when this program is executed?
‚ùå WRONG CODE
class Test {
    Test(int x) {
        System.out.println(x);
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Test t = new Test();   // error
    }
}

‚úîÔ∏è CORRECT CODE
class Test {
    Test() {
        System.out.println("Default");
    }

    Test(int x) {
        System.out.println(x);
    }
}

Concept: If a parameterized constructor exists, Java does not provide a default one.
 9) ‚Äî Constructor Name Must Match Class Name
‚ùì Question
Identify the error in the constructor declaration.
‚ùå WRONG CODE
class Test {
    Automata() {
        System.out.println("Hello");
    }
}

‚úîÔ∏è CORRECT CODE
class Test {
    Test() {
        System.out.println("Hello");
    }
}
Concept: Constructor name must be exactly same as class name.
10) ‚Äî Constructor Overloading
‚ùì Question
Why does constructor overloading fail here?
‚ùå WRONG CODE
class Test {
    void Test() {
        System.out.println("Default");
    }

    Test(int x) {
        System.out.println(x);
    }
}

‚úîÔ∏è CORRECT CODE
class Test {
    Test() {
        System.out.println("Default");
    }

    Test(int x) {
        System.out.println(x);
    }
}
Concept: All overloaded constructors must be real constructors, not methods.






